Johannesburg The DA has wielded the axe on its two shadow ministers during a reshuffle of its Gauteng cabinet.</p> Those who were dropped from the cabinet include Fred Nel, who was replaced as shadow housing minister by Mervyn Cirota, who acted as the portfolio s spokesperson. </p> Another DA member of the provincial legislature (MPL) who did not survive the chop was Mike Moriarty, who was replaced as shadow finance minister by Adriana Randall. </p> DA Gauteng leader John Moodey said the reshuffle was in preparing ground for the 2019 national election. This reshuffle comes as a result of careful deliberations to strengthen our oversight role in the legislature, as the DA readies itself to govern Gauteng after the 2019 national and provincial elections, Moodey said in a statement. He could not immediately be reached for comment.</p> He said the new look team was suited to hold Gauteng Premier David Makhura and the provincial government to account.</p> Those who survived the reshuffle include MPLs Kate Lorimer (Community Safety), Jack Bloom (Health), Khume Ramulifho (Education), Janet Semple (Economic Development), Refiloe Nt sekhe (Social Development), Alan Fuchs (Infrastructure Development), and Kingsol Chabalala (Sport, Recreation, Arts and Culture).</p> Nt sekhe also serves as the DA national spokesperson, while Ramulifho is the party s regional secretary.</p> [email&#160;protected] </p> @luyolomkentane The Star</p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </td></tr></tbody>Johannesburg The DA has wielded the axe on its two shadow ministers during a reshuffle of its Gauteng cabinet. Those who were dropped from the cabinet include Fred Nel, who was replaced as shadow housing minister by Mervyn Cirota, who acted as the portfolio s spokesperson. </p> Another DA member of the provincial legislature (MPL) who did not survive the chop was Mike Moriarty, who was replaced as shadow finance minister by Adriana Randall. </p> DA Gauteng leader John Moodey said the reshuffle was in preparing ground for the 2019 national election. This reshuffle comes as a result of careful deliberations to strengthen our oversight role in the legislature, as the DA readies itself to govern Gauteng after the 2019 national and provincial elections, Moodey said in a statement. He could not immediately be reached for comment.</p> He said the new look team was suited to hold Gauteng Premier David Makhura and the provincial government to account.</p> Those who survived the reshuffle include MPLs Kate Lorimer (Community Safety), Jack Bloom (Health), Khume Ramulifho (Education), Janet Semple (Economic Development), Refiloe Nt sekhe (Social Development), Alan Fuchs (Infrastructure Development), and Kingsol Chabalala (Sport, Recreation, Arts and Culture).</p> Nt sekhe also serves as the DA national spokesperson, while Ramulifho is the party s regional secretary.</p> [email&#160;protected] </p> @luyolomkentane The Star</p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> Those who were dropped from the cabinet include Fred Nel, who was replaced as shadow housing minister by Mervyn Cirota, who acted as the portfolio s spokesperson. Another DA member of the provincial legislature (MPL) who did not survive the chop was Mike Moriarty, who was replaced as shadow finance minister by Adriana Randall. DA Gauteng leader John Moodey said the reshuffle was in preparing ground for the 2019 national election. This reshuffle comes as a result of careful deliberations to strengthen our oversight role in the legislature, as the DA readies itself to govern Gauteng after the 2019 national and provincial elections, Moodey said in a statement. He could not immediately be reached for comment.He said the new look team was suited to hold Gauteng Premier David Makhura and the provincial government to account.Those who survived the reshuffle include MPLs Kate Lorimer (Community Safety), Jack Bloom (Health